# Simple Architecture Principle

Use this alongside **[`.cursor/rules/subject-based-thinking.mdc`](.cursor/rules/subject-based-thinking.mdc)**. Goal: **shallow trees**, **visible boundaries** (props, emits, slots), and **MVB-sized** units—deferring organizational detail to SBT. Concepts from Vasilen Lubomirov’s *Simple Architecture Principle* series (Medium).

## North star

- Prefer **flat** composition over deep nesting **until** simpler tools are exhausted (MVB, slots, composables).
- **Dependencies must be visible** at component boundaries; avoid “smart leaves” that hide side effects and service calls inside presentational names.

## Minimum Viable Behavior (MVB)

- A component should do **only** what its name implies; push unrelated concerns to parents, slots, or composables.
- If reuse requires a dozen modes or flags, the unit has grown past MVB—split or use a **Recipe** (below).

## Presentational vs orchestrating

- **Presentational (dumb):** MVB + clear `defineProps` / `defineEmits`, optional **slots** for extension. Minimal side effects.
- **Orchestrating (smart / page-level):** owns wiring—**imports composables**, loads data, decides what to show. Keep presentational children thin.

## Content projection (Vue slots)

- Prefer **slots** and parent-side wiring over one shared child with many behavioral modes and hidden `inject`/`provide` or app services **inside** a low-level control.
- Parent composes toolbar/actions; child exposes layout + inputs.

```vue
<!-- Presentational shell: behavior owned by parent via slots -->
<script setup lang="ts">
const text = defineModel<string>({ required: true })
const emit = defineEmits<{ submit: [] }>()
</script>
<template>
  <div class="rounded border p-2">
    <slot name="toolbar" />
    <textarea v-model="text" class="w-full" @keydown.enter.prevent="emit('submit')" />
    <slot name="footer" />
  </div>
</template>
```

## Composable behavior

- Put **single-purpose** logic in **`useX.ts`** composables (MVB for logic). Orchestrating SFCs **compose** them; avoid huge inline `setup` blocks.

```ts
// useChat.ts — one concern (e.g. send/stream); orchestrator composes with other useX modules.
import { ref } from 'vue'

export function useChat() {
  const streamingText = ref('')
  function sendMessage() {
    /* … */
  }
  return { sendMessage, streamingText }
}
```

## Subject-based structure (see SBT rule)

Canonical detail: **[`.cursor/rules/subject-based-thinking.mdc`](.cursor/rules/subject-based-thinking.mdc)**. Short alignment:

- Organize by **subject** (real-world / product concept), not only by screen position. Before adding files: *What is the subject? Can everything related live together?*
- A **subject capsule** holds the **vertical slice** when practical: UI, composables, data access, types/schemas, and co-located **`*.backend.ts`** in this repo.
- Default new **Kota0** behavior under **`app/src/components/kota0/<subject>/`** (see SBT rule); keep cross-subject code **thin** in `app/src/lib/` and `shared/`. Treat subject folders as **boundaries**; avoid cross-subject leaks unless work is explicitly integration.

## Recipes (single-purpose components)

- When an orchestrating view becomes mostly **imports and glue**, extract a **Recipe**: one **concrete** use case, combining building blocks + composables **without** a universal prop matrix.
- **Prefer a new recipe** (e.g. per subject) over `mode` / `isForX` sprawl. Recipes **live inside** the subject tree—they do **not** replace subject capsules.

## Avoid

- Universal mega-wrappers, prop explosion, configuration towers as the default fix.
- Duplicating **domain** policy inside presentational components.
